Well use data on housing values in suburbs of Boston. They are in an R package called MASS. (An R package is a collection of code, data, and documentation. MASS refers to the book Modern Applied Statistics with S. R developed from the earlier language, S.) The MASS package comes with the default R installation, so its already on your computer. However, its not loaded into your R session by default. So well load it via the require() command (theres nothing for you to do here):

require("MASS")
## Loading required package: MASS

Make a density plot (with rug) of tax rates.

plot(density(Boston$tax), main = "Tax Rate Density Histogram", xlab = "Tax Rate Per $10,000"); rug(Boston$tax)

Describe the shape of the distribution of tax rates. The density plot has a bimodal distribution with much of the data centered around a tax rate of 300 and a smaller peak at approximately 675.

Note that the distribution shape doesnt make sense in light of the rug representation of the data. Make a histogram of the tax rates.

hist(Boston$tax, main = "Boston Tax Rates", xlab = "Tax Rate Per $10,000")

Why is the second peak of the density plot so large? In what way is the rug representation of the data inadequate? Write a line or two of code to figure it out, and then explain it.

hist(Boston$tax, 5); rug(Boston$tax)

The second peak is so big because of the large number of outliers are all located in a similar range of values. The data is skewed left and those outliers pull the mean of the data set to a greater value than the median.

Look into the highest-crime neighborhood by making a single graph of one column of three rows:

  • Find the row number, r, of the neighborhood with the highest crim.
  • Make a density plot of crim. Include a rug to show the data.
  • Add a red circle at (x, y) = (max crime rate, 0) to make this maximum crime rate stand out.
  • Make a density plot with rug of medv, adding a red circle at (x, y) = (medv[r], 0) to see what medv corresponds to the highest crime rate.
  • Repeat the last step for ptratio.
max(Boston$crim)
## [1] 88.9762
plot(density(Boston$crim), main = "Boston Crime Rates", xlab = "Crime Rates"); rug(Boston$crim); points(88.9762,0,pch = 16, col = "red")

plot(density(Boston$medv), main = "Boston Median Values of Homes in $1000s", xlab = "Median Value of Homes in $1000s"); rug(Boston$medv); points(10.4,0, pch = 16, col = "red")

plot(density(Boston$ptratio), main = "Boston Pupil-Teacher Ratios", xlab = "Pupil-Teacher Ratio"); rug(Boston$ptratio); points(20.2,0, pch = 16, col = "red")

What do you notice about the ptratio and medv for the highest-crime neighborhood?

The median value of homes is low and the pupil-teacher ratio is large for the highest crime neighborhood.
